value.value: A diagnostic procedure during surgery in which dye is injected into the cystic duct to visualize the anatomy of the gallbladder and bile ducts.
The use of an endoscope during a surgical procedure to either diagnose or treat a disorder.
Placement of a catheter into the intrathecal space of the spine.
Placement of a pump device that delivers medication into the intrathecal space of the spine.
Continuous intravenous administration of a solution with lidocaine.
A deficiency of iodine in the diet.
Visualization of the knee joint with an arthroscope.
A surgical procedure to replace part or all of a knee joint with an orthopedic prosthesis.
The creation of an internal ileal pouch that is connected to an abdominal stoma with a valve to prevent leakage.
A laparoscopic procedure in which a band is placed around the stomach to decrease the size of the stomach, which contributes to a fuller feeling and assists with losing weight.

The hydrochloride form of eflornithine, a difluoromethylated ornithine compound with antineoplastic activity.  Eflornithine irreversibly inhibits ornithine decarboxylase, an enzyme required for polyamine biosynthesis, thereby inhibiting the formation and proliferation of tumor cells. Polyamines are involved in nucleosome oligomerization and DNA conformation, creating a chromatin environment that stimulates neoplastic transformation of cells. (NCI04)
Clinical trials that study ways of reducing the risk of getting cancer.
A surgical procedure in which a portion of the upper stomach is wrapped around the lower esophageal sphincter to reinforce it and prevent reflux.
The use of a laser that vaporizes layers of skin to resurface it and remove imperfections and make it smoother.
The use of a laser to break apart the ink in a tattoo, which is then reabsorbed and the tattoo dissolves.
The use of a laser beam to destroy a vein, which is done either externally or internally when a laser catheter is passed into the vein.
The use of a laser to change the shape of the cornea to improve vision.
Blocking the flow of blood from the appendage in the left atrium to reduce the risk of clots entering the bloodstream.
A change in the function, shape or size of the left ventricle, which can be either physiological or pathological. A decline in performance is the result.
A laparoscopic procedure that implants a ring of magnetic core titanium beads at the lower esophageal sphincter to stop acid and food regurgitation into the esophagus.
The removal of excess fat deposits from the body.

Steps towards preventing damage to the liver which can include vaccinations against hepatitis A and B, healthy diet, regular exercise, moderate alcohol intake, proper use of medications and avoiding contact with other's blood and body fluids.
Small-scale testing (usually on SBIRs) of new technology in a small group of patients or normal volunteers. Does not meet the rigorous criteria of a clinical trial.
A diet that restricts the consumption of fermentable oligo-, di-, mono-saccharides and polyols, which are short chain carbohydrates that are poorly absorbed in the small intestine.
Any surgical treatments on the bowel, which includes the duodenum, jejunum and the ileum.
Surgery to minimize or eliminate a neoplastic process in the lungs.
Surgery to remove diseased lung tissue, which is often emphysematous. This reduces the size of the lung, and allows expansion of more healthy lung tissue.
Treatment targeted at the lymphatic system, often to reduce excess lymph fluid that can be caused by injury, cancer treatments, infection or a birth defect.

A method for brachytherapy that uses an implanted catheter to deliver a radioactive seed into the breast site. During a lumpectomy procedure a catheter with a balloon tip is temporarily implanted into the site where the tumor was removed. After surgery a radioactive seed is fed through the catheter to the tumor site.
Uncontrolled bleeding from a pregnant or a woman who has recently given birth.
A pathologic response to infection in a mother or pregnant woman.
Surgery to reposition the bones of the upper and lower jaw to relieve airway obstruction.
Surgery on a mass located on the mediastinum.

The interaction of a recipient's (patient's) immune system with an organ or tissue graft, or with the reactivity of donor-derived passenger leukocytes in the graft with the host's (patient's) body. (NCI/OSP)
Surgery to remove or treat a melanoma.
Surgery to remove or treat a meningioma.
Surgical procedures on the heart that are performed through small incisions in the chest, sometimes with a robot assistant.
Surgery to replace a joint that is performed that use smaller incisions and less cutting than a traditional surgery for replacement.

Surgical removal of a melanoma in which the skin is removed one layer at a time followed by microscopic evaluation for cancer cells. Successive layers are removed whenever cancer cells are found in the previous layer.

Surgical removal of non-melanoma cancer in which the skin is removed one layer at a time followed by microscopic evaluation for cancer cells. Successive layers are removed whenever cancer cells are found in the previous layer.
The use of magnetic resonance to guide and control the delivery of energy to destroy a target and not damage surrounding tissue.
Surgical procedures to treat the complications of multiple myeloma. It can be performed to strengthen and stabilize bones.
Treatment programs that use strategies to maintain function, participation and quality of life for individuals with multiple sclerosis.
Treatment programs that use strategies to maintain function, participation and quality of life for individuals with musculoskeletal disorders.

Conduct clinical trials and develop new trial methodologies. Trials should be designed in order to rapidly develop new therapeutic strategies, optimize clinical efficacy and proper use of available modalities, define factors that affect the success of therapeutic strategies (including the role of resistance), and advance our understanding of disease pathogenesis and progression.
Surgical procedures for non-melanoma cancers which involve removing the cancer, repairing the site, possibly removing the lymph nodes and reducing of pain.
Surgery on the nose or nasal passages.
Heart valve repair that use techniques that preserve as much of the natural heart valve structure as possible.
The construction of a new bladder with intestinal tissue.
Treatment programs that use strategies to maintain function, participation and quality of life for individuals with neurological disorders.
